gy in the Faroe Islands}}\nIn 2014 217,547 tonnes of oil products were consumed in the Faroe Islands.<ref name=\"oilcons\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hagstova.fo/en/statbank/consumption-oil-tonnes-consumer-groups-1992- | title=Consumption of oil in tonnes by consumer groups | publisher=[[Statistics Faroe Islands]] | accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref> Of this 31.58% was consumed by fishing vessels, 14.73% was used by [[SEV (company)|SEV]] for electricity production, 23.23% was consumed in air, sea or land transport, 9.6 was used in the industry, and the rest was used in public or private buildings.<ref name=\"oilcons\" />\n\nThe islands have 6 hydroelectric plants,<ref>[http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=149 Hydro electric power]</ref> 4 diesel plants<ref>[http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=148 Thermal Power]</ref> and several wind power plants with a [[capacity factor]] above 40%.<ref name=windTerji>Terji Nielsen. [http://www.jf.fo/get.file?ID=13677 Wind energy in the Faroe Islands] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208235240/http://www.jf.fo/get.file?ID=13677 |date=2015-12-08 }} page 19-21. ''SEV'', 2015</ref> In 2014, a 12MW [[wind farm]] for DKK 180 million<ref name=sevGreenProgress/> became operational near Torshavn and increased wind capacity from 6.6 to 18.6MW. It decreases oil consumption by 8,000 ton (approximately 4M\u20ac) per year.<ref name=windTerji/> A 2.3MW 700 kWh [[lithium-ion battery]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://reneweconomy.com.au/2015/faroe-islands-to-get-europes-first-wind-connected-battery-storage-system-30393 |title=Faroe Islands to get Europe's first wind-connected battery storage system |work=Renew Economy}}</ref> became operational in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://eandt.theiet.org/content/articles/2016/11/lithium-ion-batteries-can-help-to-safeguard-the-grid/ |title=Lithium-ion batteries can help to safeguard the grid|publisher= |date=8 November 2016|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> Planners also consider converting the existing [[hydropower]]<ref>B\u00e1r\u00f0ur A. Niclasen. [http://www.jardfeingi.fo/get.file?ID=13697 Vedvarende energi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208054059/http://www.jardfeingi.fo/get.file?ID=13697 |date=2015-12-08 }} 2015</ref> to [[pumped-storage hydroelectricity]].<ref name=sevGreenProgress/> [[Tidal power]]<ref>[http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=193&Action=1&NewsId=2765&PID=392 Tidal Energy on the Horizon]</ref> and [[Thermal energy storage]] solutions are also considered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tu.no/kraft/2015/11/27/faroyene-vurderer-norsk-teknologi-for-a-takle-massiv-vindkraftutbygging |title=ENERGYNEST - THERMAL ENERGY STORAGE - TES|author=Jannicke Nilsen |date=27 November 2015|work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]}}</ref> The islands have a goal of 100% green electricity production by 2030.<ref name=sevGreenProgress>[http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=193&Action=1&NewsId=2778&PID=392 Green Progress]</ref><ref name=100by2030>{{cite web|url=http://www.100by2030.org/ |title=100by2030 |work=[[SEV (company)|SEV]] |accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{external image\n| image1 =[http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=200 Current production, pie diagram]\n| image2 =[https://w3.sev.fo/framleidsla/ Current production, numbers]\n}}\n\nIn 2014 and 2017<ref>http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=193&Action=1&NewsId=3008&M=NewsV2&PID=392</ref> 50.8% of the electricity production of SEV in the Faroe Islands came from green energy like hydro and wind, while 49.2% was produced by the [[thermal power plant]]s, which was 12.4% less than in 2013.<ref name=\"SEV 2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sev.fo/Files//Filer/Um_sev/fradgreidingar/SEV_framleidsluroknskapur_2014.pdf|title=SEV - Framlei\u00f0sluroknskapur 2014 Production Accounts 2014|publisher=SEV|language=Faroese, English|accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n*''fossil fuel:'' 49.2%\n*''hydro:'' 39.5%\n*''wind:'' 11.3%% (2014)\n*''nuclear:'' 0%\n\nTotal annual production: 305.4 GWh (2014) of which the production of thermal, hydropower and [[wind power]] was:\n*Thermal: 150,2 GWh\n*Hydropower: 120,7 GWh\n*Wind: 34,5 GWh\n\nThe Faroe Islands have no electricity connections to other areas, and thus operate in [[Islanding|island condition]]. Some islands are also not connected to the other islands, and must maintain their own electric system.<ref>[http://www.sev.fo/Default.aspx?ID=193&Action=1&NewsId=2774&PID=392 SEV recommends wind turbines for Su\u00f0uroy]</ref>\n\n== Other ==\n\n'''Agriculture - products:'''\n[[milk]], [[potato]]es, [[vegetable]]s; [[domestic sheep|sheep]]; [[salmon]], other [[fish]]\n\n'''Currency:'''\n1 Danish krone (DKr) = 100 \u00f8rer\n\n'''Exchange rates:'''\nDanish kroner (DKr) per US$1 \u2013 5.560 (2008), 7.336 (January 2000), 6.976 (1999), 6.701 (1998), 6.604 (1997), 5.799 (1996), 5.602 (1995)\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.faroeseseafood.com www.FaroeseSeafood.com] - Information site on fisheries and aquaculture in the Faroe Islands{{refbegin}}\n* Apostle, Richard A. ''The Restructuration of the Faroese Economy The Significance of the Inner Periphery''. Frederiksberg, Denmark: Samfundslitteratur, 2002. {{ISBN|87-593-0891-5}}\n* Elkj\u00e6r-Hansen, Niels. ''The Faroe Islands Scenery, Culture, and Economy''. Copenhagen: Royal Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 1959.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081118143151/http://www.hagstova.fo/portal/page/portal/SHARED/HAGSTOVA_MAIN_TEMPLATE/Faroe%20Islands%20in%20figures%202008.pdf Hagstova.fo]\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nationalbanken.dk/DNUK/NotesAndCoins.nsf/side/The_new_Faroese_banknote_series?OpenDocument Faroese banknote series] Information about Faroese banknotes\n{{-}}\n\n{{Faroe Islands topics}}\n{{Economy of Europe}}\n{{EU Dependent economies|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Economy of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Economies by country|Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Economies of Europe by dependent territory|+Faroe Islands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox economy\n|country = Faroe Islands\n|image = Vestaravag torshavn, faroe islands, feb 2005.jpg \n|width = \n|caption = [[T\u00f3rshavn]] is the capital and largest town of the [[Faroe Islands]]\n|currency = [[Faroese kr\u00f3na]] (pegged with [[Danish krone]], (DKK)) \n|year = calendar year\n|organs = none <!--?are they in any?-->\n|gdp rank = [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|166th]] (nominal) / [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|179th]] (PPP)\n|gdp = $1.471 billion (2013 est.)<ref>[http://www.hagstova.fo/fo/tidindi/2015/02/helvtin-av-vokstrinum-i-btu-stavar-fra-fiskaalingini Hagstova.fo (Faroese Statistics)]</ref>\n|growth =7.5% (2013 est.)\n|per capita = $45,709 (2010 est.)\n|sectors = agriculture: 16%, industry: 29%, services: 55% (2007)\n|inflation = 2.3% (2011)\n|poverty = no data\n|labor = 34,710 (March 2010)\n|occupations = agriculture: 10.7%, industry: 18.9%, services: 70.3% (2010)\n|unemployment = 1% in 2019,<ref name=unempl2019/> down from 5.5% in May 2012<ref>[http://www.hagstova.fo/portal/page/portal/HAGSTOVAN/Hagstova_Foroya Official Faroese Statistics (Faroese)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210030515/http://www.hagstova.fo/portal/page/portal/HAGSTOVAN/Hagstova_Foroya |date=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n|industries = [[fishing]], [[fish processing]], [[fish farming]], small ship repair and refurbishment, handicrafts\n|exports = DKK 9 billion by 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=Exports exceed DKK 9 billion |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2019/11/24/exports-exceed-dkk-9-billion |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |last1=Djurhuus |first1=H\u00f8gni |language=fo |date=24 November 2019}}</ref> <!-- was $824 million f.o.b. (2010 est.) -->\n|export-goods = fish and fish products 90%, stamps, ships\n|export-partners = {{flag|Russia}} 23.8% <br/>  {{flag|United States}} 11.2%<br/> {{flag|United Kingdom}} 10.6% <br/> {{flag|Denmark}} 7.7% <br/> {{flag|China}} 7.1%  <br/> {{flag|Germany}} 6.5% <br/> {{flag|Norway}} 5.7% (2016)<ref name=\"exports\" />\n|imports = $776 million c.i.f. (2010 est.)\n|import-goods = consumer goods 24%, machinery and transport equipment 23.5%, fuels 21.4%, raw materials and semi-manufactures, fish, salt\n|import-partners = {{flag|Denmark}} 37.4% <br/> {{flag|Germany}} 13.3% <br/> {{flag|Norway}} 9.3% <br/> {{flag|China}} 5.6% <br/> {{flag|Sweden}} 4.3% <br/> {{flag|Iceland}} 3.8% (2016)<ref name=\"imports\" />\n|debt = $888.8 million (2010)\n|revenue = $1.22 billion (2010)\n|expenses = $1.301 billion (2010)\n|aid = ''recipient'': $100 million (annual subsidy from Denmark) (2007)\n|cianame = fo\n}}\n\nThe '''economy of the Faroe Islands''' was the 166th largest in the world in 2014, having a nominal [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) of $2.613 billion per annum.<ref name=\"World Bank GDP (nominal)\">{{cite web|title=Gross domestic product 2014|url=http://databank.worldbank.org/data/download/GDP.pdf |publisher=[[World Bank]]|accessdate=12 October 2015|format=PDF|date=18 September 2015}}</ref> The vast majority of Faroese exports, around 90%, consists of fishery products.<ref name=fi-economy/>\n\n==History==\nAfter the severe economic troubles of the early 1990s, brought on by a drop in the vital [[fish]] catch and poor management of the economy, the [[Faroe Islands]] have recently recovered, with unemployment down to 5% in mid-1998, and holding below 3% since 2006, one of the lowest rates in [[Europe]].\n\n==Challenges and opportunities==\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb = right\n| caption = Salaries by industry, 2019<ref name=\"salary2019\">{{cite web |title=Salaries exceeded DKK 10 billion last year |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2020/01/11/salaries-exceeded-dkk-10-billion-last-year |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |language=fo |last1=Djurhuus |first1=H\u00f8gni |date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| other =\n| label1 =Service\n| value1 =64\n| color1 =yellow\n| label2 = Fishing & farming\n| value2 =20\n| color2 =blue\n| label3 =Construction & manufacturing\n| value3 =16\n| color3 =olive\n| label4 =\n| value4 =0\n| color4 =brown\n| label5 =\n| value5 =0\n| color5 =gold\n| label6 = \n| value6 =0\n| color6 =red\n}}\nHigh dependence on [[fishing]] (including [[salmon farming]]) means the [[Faroe Islands]]' economy remains vulnerable. The Faroese hope to broaden their economic base by building new fish-processing plants. The islands allow up to 25% foreign ownership of ocean industry decreasing gradually until 2032 when foreign ownership must end.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hvidtfeldt |first1=J\u00f3n Brian |title=Foreign ownership in fishery industry continues |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2019/12/23/foreign-ownership-fishery-industry-continues |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |language=fo |date=23 December 2019}}</ref> [[Petroleum]] found close to the Faroese area gives hope for deposits in the immediate area, which may lay the basis for sustained economic prosperity.  Also important are the annual subsidy from [[Denmark]], which amounted{{when|date=January 2020}} to about 3% of the GDP.<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/fo.html Information about the economy of the Faroe Islands]</ref>\n\nThe Faroes have one of the lowest unemployment rates in Europe (1% in 2019),<ref name=unempl2019>{{cite web |last1=Djurhuus |first1=H\u00f8gni |title=Enough funds to cover 12 years of unemployment |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2020/01/13/enough-funds-cover-12-years-unemployment |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |language=fo |date=13 January 2020}}</ref> but this is not necessarily a sign of a recovering economy, as many young students move to Denmark and other countries once they are finished with high school. This leaves a largely middle-aged and elderly population that may lack the skills and knowledge to take IT positions in business and industry. Since 2000, new [[information technology]] and business projects have been fostered in the Faroe Islands to attract new investment. The result from these projects is not yet known but is hoped to bring a better market economy to the Faroe Islands.{{cn| date=January 2020}} The population was around 52,000 by 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Population now close to 52,000 |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2019/11/15/population-now-close-52000 |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |language=fo}}</ref>\n\nGeneral salaries increased from DKK 7 billion in 2013 to DKK 10 billion in 2019.<ref name=\"salary2019\"/>\n\n==Trade==\nIn 2014 the [[Faroe Islands]] had a [[trade surplus]] of 401 million [[Danish krone|DKK]],<ref name=\"stats2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hagstova.fo/sites/default/files/Faroe_Islands_in_figures_2015.pdf |title=Faroe Islands in Figures 2015 |publisher=[[Statistics Faroe Islands]] |accessdate=5 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000633/http://www.hagstova.fo/sites/default/files/Faroe_Islands_in_figures_2015.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> a figure that rose to 1.43 billion DKK in 2016.<ref name=\"stats2017\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hagstova.fo/sites/default/files/Faroe_Islands_in_figures_2017.pdf |title=Faroe Islands in Figures 2017 |publisher=[[Statistics Faroe Islands]] |accessdate=5 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130128/http://www.hagstova.fo/sites/default/files/Faroe_Islands_in_figures_2017.pdf |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  As of 2016, the Faroe Islands mainly imported goods from [[Denmark]] (2,467 million DKK), [[Germany]] (877 million DKK), and [[Norway]] (610 DKK).<ref name=\"imports\">{{cite web | url=http://statbank.hagstova.fo/pxweb/en/H2/H2__UH__UH01/uh_innbec.px/table/tableViewLayout1/?rxid=84e5f2ec-f7f8-454d-87cc-452a5cad5ae7 | title=Import by BEC-groups, country of origin and months (1988-2017) | publisher=[[Statistics Faroe Islands]] | accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref> The country's top export destinations were [[Russia]] (1,907 million DKK), the United States (898 million DKK), the United Kingdom (851 million DKK),  and Denmark (697 million DKK).<ref name=\"exports\">{{cite web | url=http://statbank.hagstova.fo/pxweb/en/H2/H2__UH__UH01/uh_utlond.px/table/tableViewLayout1/?rxid=84e5f2ec-f7f8-454d-87cc-452a5cad5ae7 | title=Exports by country of final destination (1988-2016)| publisher=[[Statistics Faroe Islands]] | accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref> European Union countries constituted 72.9% of total Faroese imports, while the exports of the Faroe Islands were more equally distributed between European Union (44.4%) and non-European Union countries (55.6%).<ref name=\"stats2017\" /> The vast majority of Faroese exports, around 90%, consists of fishery products.<ref name=fi-economy>{{cite web |title=Economy of the Faroe Islands |url=https://www.visitfaroeislands.com/about/history-governance-economy/economy/ |website=Visit Faroe Islands |accessdate=18 January 2020}}<!--no date. archive blocked--></ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.visitfaroeislands.com/en/about-the-faroe-islands/trade-and-industry/ | title=Trade and Industry | publisher=VisitFaroeIslands.com | accessdate=5 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151208130940/http://www.visitfaroeislands.com/en/about-the-faroe-islands/trade-and-industry | archive-date=8 December 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis#Sanctions by Russia|Russian countersanctions]] on food imports from Norway and the European Union, saw the Faroe Islands increase its fresh salmon exports to Russia.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://barentsobserver.com/en/business/2015/09/faroe-islands-cashing-russian-sanctions-03-09 | title=Faroe Islands cashing in on Russian sanctions | publisher=Barents Observer | date=September 3, 2015 | accessdate=5 December 2015 | author=Pettersen, Trude}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://murmur.dk/articles/the-faroe-islands-dont-play-by-eu-rules.383.html | title=The Faroe Islands don't play by EU rules | publisher=The Murmur | date=18 October 2015 | accessdate=5 December 2015 | author=Rutkowski, Lena | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208074117/http://murmur.dk/articles/the-faroe-islands-dont-play-by-eu-rules.383.html | archive-date=8 December 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Faroe/Russian fishery agreement renewed |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2019/12/10/faroerussian-fishery-agreement-renewed |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |language=fo |date=10 December 2019}}</ref> The Faroe Islands has a [[free trade agreement]] with Iceland since 2005.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johannessen |first1=John |title=Faroe/Iceland free trade deal renewed |url=https://kvf.fo/greinar/2019/12/29/faroeiceland-free-trade-deal-renewed |website=Kringvarp F\u00f8roya |language=fo |date=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n  \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:600px;\"\n|+'''Imports and exports in 2014; values in million [[Danish krone]] (DKK)'''<ref name=\"stats2017\" /><ref name=\"imports\" /><ref name=\"exports\" />\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center; vertical-align:middle;\"\n! Rank rowspan=\"2\"|Rank !! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:150px;\"|Imports !! rowspan=\"2\"|Rank !! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:150px;\"|Exports\n|-\n! Origin !! Value !! Destination !! Value\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{DEN}} || 2,467 DKK || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{RUS}} || 1,907 DKK \n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{GER}} || 897 DKK || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{USA}} || 898 DKK\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{NOR}} || 610 DKK || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{UK}} || 851 DKK\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4 || style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{CHN}} || 371 DKK || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4 || style=\"text-al