{"title_page": "Lebanon\u2013Syria border", "text_new": "[[File:Lebanon Physiography.jpg|thumb|right|Map of Lebanon]]\nThe '''Lebanon\u2013Syria border''' is 394 km (245 m) in length and runs from the Mediterranean coast in the north to the tripoint with [[Israel]] in the south.<ref>{{cite|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sy|title=CIA World Factbook \u2013 Syria|accessdate= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe border starts at confluence of the [[Nahr al-Kabir]] river with the [[Mediterranean Sea]], and then follows this river eastwards some distance inland. The Lebanese border forms a [[Salient (geography)|salient]] to include the villages of Karha and Knaisse Akkar in the north-east of [[Akkar District]], just west of the Syrian [[Lake Homs]], before turning to the south-east via a series of irregular lines, cutting across the [[Orontes River|Orontes]] (at {{coord|34.455|N|36.490|E|}}) and the [[Beqaa Valley|trans-Beqaa]] road between [[Qaa]] and [[Al-Qusayr, Syria|Al-Qusayr]] (at {{coord|34.4217|N|36.5433|E|}}), reaching the [[Anti-Lebanon mountains]] at about {{coord|34.22|N|36.60|E|}}. The border then turns towards the south-west, generally following the Anti-Lebanon mountains via a series of irregular lines, until reaching [[Mount Hermon]]. \n\nThe precise location of Lebanese-Israeli-Syrian [[tripoint]] is unclear due to Israel's [[occupation of the Golan Heights]] stemming from the 1967 [[Six Day War]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-14724842 Golan Heights profile] 25 March 2019 BBC</ref> The ''de jure'' tripoint lies on the [[Hasbani River]], a tributary of the  [[river Jordan]], at {{coord|33.2422|N|35.6244|E|}}), just north-east of the Israeli town of [[Ma'ayan Baruch]]. The ''de facto'' tripoints lie on the tripoint(s) with the Untied Nations [[UNDOF Zone]]. The situation is further complicated by the dispute over the [[Shebaa farms]] area on Golan-Lebanon border.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Understanding the Sheeba Farms dispute |url=http://www.pij.org/details.php?id=9 |first=Asher |last=Kaufman |journal=Palestine-Israel Journal |volume=11 |issue=1 |year=2004 |access-date=22 July 2006 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe border was created in 1920 under the  [[French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]], with the establishment of [[Greater Lebanon]]  (the \"Greater\" indicating the expansion of the territory of the Ottoman [[Mount Lebanon Mutasarrifate]]).  \nBut due to the history of [[Syrian occupation of Lebanon|Syrian political involvement with Lebanon]] since the 1970s, the border has never been fixed officially with any precision, in spite of Lebanese demands to this effect,<ref>see [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1680]] (2006)</ref> and the border's demarcation on Syrian and Lebanese maps shows considerable discrepancies in details. The village of [[Deir El Aachayer]] (west of [[Damascus]]) is an example of a territory claimed by both countries on their respective official maps.{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe [[Shebaa farms]] were long shown as Syrian territory on Lebanese maps during Israel's occupation of the Golan Heights, but after Israeli withdrawal from Southern Lebanon in 2000 it was claimed by Lebanon.\n\n==Border crossings==\n* [[Arida Border Crossing]]<ref name=\"Bradt\">Paul Doyle, (2012) ''Bradt Travel Guide - Lebanon'', pgs. 51-2</ref>\n* [[Jusiyah al-Amar]]-[[Qaa]] Border Crossing<ref name=\"Bradt\"/>\n* [[Masnaa Border Crossing]], on the road between Damascus and Beirut<ref name=\"Bradt\"/>\n* [[Dabousieh]] Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* [[Talkalakh]] Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* Zemrani Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* Hamra Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lebanon\u2013Syria relations]]\n*[[Syrian Civil War spillover in Lebanon]]\n*[[Lebanon\u2013Syria border clashes]]\n\n{{Borders of Lebanon}}\n{{Borders of Syria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebanon-Syria border}}\n[[Category:Lebanon\u2013Syria border| ]]\n[[Category:Borders of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Borders of Syria]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lebanon Physiography.jpg|thumb|right|Map of Lebanon]]\nThe '''Lebanon\u2013Syria border''' is 394 km (245 m) in length and runs from the Mediterranean coast in the north to the tripoint with [[Israel]] in the south.<ref>{{cite|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sy|title=CIA World Factbook \u2013 Syria|accessdate= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe border starts at confluence of the [[Nahr al-Kabir]] river with the [[Mediterranean Sea]], and then follows this river eastwards some distance inland. The Lebanese border forms a [[Salient (geography)|salient]] to include the villages of Karha and Knaisse Akkar in the north-east of [[Akkar District]], just west of the Syrian [[Lake Homs]], before turning to the south-east via a series of irregular lines, cutting across the [[Orontes River|Orontes]] (at {{coord|34.455|N|36.490|E|}}) and the [[Beqaa Valley|trans-Beqaa]] road between [[Qaa]] and [[Al-Qusayr, Syria|Al-Qusayr]] (at {{coord|34.4217|N|36.5433|E|}}), reaching the [[Anti-Lebanon mountains]] at about {{coord|34.22|N|36.60|E|}}. The border then turns towards the south-west, generally following the Anti-Lebanon mountains via a series of irregular lines, until reaching [[Mount Hermon]]. \n\nThe precise location of Lebanese-Israeli-Syrian [[tripoint]] is unclear due to Israel's [[occupation of the Golan Heights]] stemming from the 1967 [[Six Day War]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-14724842 Golan Heights profile] 25 March 2019 BBC</ref> The ''de jure'' tripoint lies on the [[Hasbani River]], a tributary of the  [[river Jordan]], at {{coord|33.2422|N|35.6244|E|}}), just north-east of the Israeli town of [[Ma'ayan Baruch]]. The ''de facto'' tripoints lie on the tripoint(s) with the Untied Nations [[UNDOF Zone]]. The situation is further complicated by the dispute over the [[Shebaa farms]] area on Golan-Lebanon border.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Understanding the Sheeba Farms dispute |url=http://www.pij.org/details.php?id=9 |first=Asher |last=Kaufman |journal=Palestine-Israel Journal |volume=11 |issue=1 |year=2004 |access-date=22 July 2006 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe border was created in 1920 under the  [[French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]], with the establishment of [[Greater Lebanon]]  (the \"Greater\" indicating the expansion of the territory of the Ottoman [[Mount Lebanon Mutasarrifate]]).  \nBut due to the history of [[Syrian occupation of Lebanon|Syrian political involvement with Lebanon]] since the 1970s, the border has never been fixed officially with any precision, in spite of Lebanese demands to this effect,<ref>see [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1680]] (2006)</ref> and the border's demarcation on Syrian and Lebanese maps shows considerable discrepancies in details. The village of [[Deir El Aachayer]] (west of [[Damascus]]) is an example of a territory claimed by both countries on their respective official maps.{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe [[Shebaa farms]] were long shown as Syrian territory on Lebanese maps during Israel's occupation of the Golan Heights, but after Israeli withdrawal from Southern Lebanon in 2000 it was claimed by Lebanon.\n\n==Border Crossings==\n* [[Arida Border Crossing]]<ref name=\"Bradt\">Paul Doyle, (2012) ''Bradt Travel Guide - Lebanon'', pgs. 51-2</ref>\n* [[Jusiyah al-Amar]]-[[Qaa]] Border Crossing<ref name=\"Bradt\"/>\n* [[Masnaa Border Crossing]], on the road between Damascus and Beirut<ref name=\"Bradt\"/>\n* [[Dabousieh]] Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* [[Talkalakh]] Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* Zemrani Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* Hamra Border Crossing{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lebanon\u2013Syria relations]]\n*[[Syrian Civil War spillover in Lebanon]]\n*[[Lebanon\u2013Syria border clashes]]\n\n{{Borders of Lebanon}}\n{{Borders of Syria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebanon-Syria border}}\n[[Category:Lebanon\u2013Syria border| ]]\n[[Category:Borders of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Borders of Syria]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "name_user": "WisDom-UK", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBorder Crossings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebanon%E2%80%93Syria_border"}
{"title_page": "PRAN-RFL Group", "text_new": "{{about|the brand|other uses|Pran (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n'''PRAN-RFL Group''' ({{lang-bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a3-\u0986\u09b0\u098f\u09ab\u098f\u09b2 \u0997\u09cd\u09b0\u09c1\u09aa}}) is one of the largest conglomerates in [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-20358|title=Pran to build first foreign plant in India|date=24 January 2008|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> It is the largest [[agribusiness]] in Bangladesh.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-214548|title=Pran makes it big in dairy business|date=18 December 2011|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> Founder (Masum Reza) \n\n== History ==\nPRAN (Programme for Rural Advancement Nationally)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/first-bangladeshi-food-processing-unit-in-india-115060400454_1.html|title=First Bangladeshi food processing unit in India|last=IANS|date=4 June 2015|work=Business Standard India|access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref> was established in 1981 by retired Major General [[Amjad Khan Chowdhury]] and has become one of the largest food and beverage brands in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/corporate/news/111259/Amjad-Khan%E2%80%99s-death-anniv-observed|title=Amjad Khan's death anniv observed|work=Prothom Alo|access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2014/03/12/22986|title=Bangladeshi agro-processed food has good prospect abroad|last=Bilkis|first=Shahana|date=12 March 2014|location=Dhaka|newspaper=The Financial Express}}</ref> PRAN pioneered agribusiness in Bangladesh by providing farmers with guaranteed prices.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BBQKr8mIcAIC&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Challenging the Injustice of Poverty: Agendas for Inclusive Development in South Asia|last=Sobhan|first=Rehman|date=4 October 2010|publisher=SAGE Publications|year=|isbn=9788132104681|location=|pages=111|language=en}}</ref> PRAN Foods, a subsidiary of the PRAN-RFL Group,<ref>{{Cite news |title=GDCL to arrange Tk 1b fund for Pran thru Islamic Bond issue |url=http://www.observerbd.com/2016/04/08/145668.php |newspaper=The Daily Observer |access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref> produces a number of agricultural products under the PRAN banner. PRAN established a subsidiary company in [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]] in 2003.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Basit |first=Abdul |title=Pran Foods expects 60% sales growth in 2014 |url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/markets/pran-foods-expects-60-sales-growth-in-2014 |work=Khaleej Times |access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref> In 2008, the company announced plans to open a production facility in [[Tripura]], [[India]], after the Indian government lifted the ban on direct investment from Bangladesh in 2007.<ref name=\":0\" /> The PRAN group's exports had reached 10&nbsp;billion [[taka]] by 2016, with the biggest markets for the company in India, [[Saudi Arabia]], the UAE, [[Malaysia]], and [[Oman]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=http://daily-sun.com/post/149798/PRANRFL-fetches-over-Tk-1000cr-from-export|title=PRAN-RFL fetches over Tk 1,000cr from export |work=Daily Sun |access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> The same year the revenue for PRAN exceeded US$500 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/56K8rW8kKBm7pN6sv6CzTO/If-Shan-doesnt-get-you-Pran-will.html|title=If Shan doesn't get you, PRAN will|last=Mitra|first=Sounak|date=10 February 2016|work=livemint.com/|access-date=1 April 2017}}</ref> PRAN started exporting potatoes in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/pran-starts-potato-export-789643|title=PRAN starts potato export|date=11 March 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> In April 2016, PRAN started to export [[cassava]] and the first shipment, worth US$3 million, was sent to New Zealand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/pran-export-3m-cassava-new-zealand-1207789|title=PRAN to export $3m of cassava to New Zealand|date=12 April 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> PRAN has 80 thousand direct employees and 200 thousand indirect employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/global-business/memory-the-man-who-built-pran-1250362|title=In memory of the man who built Pran|date=5 July 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> PRAN exports to over 118 different countries.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/149796/PRAN-aims-at-poverty-cut-employs-over-10-lakh-workers/2016-07-10|title=PRAN aims at poverty cut, employs over 10 lakh workers|date=|work=Daily Sun|access-date=1 April 2017|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Food product brands]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi brands]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Bangladesh]]\n\n\n{{company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the brand|other uses|Pran (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{infobox product\n| title            = PRAN-RFL<br />{{lang|bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a3-\u0986\u09b0\u098f\u09ab\u098f\u09b2}}\n| image            = PRAN-RFL GROUP.png\n| image_size       =250\n| alt =An image containing two logos - that of PRAN and RFL on the top and bottom, and in between them, the words[[ PRAN-RFL]] GROUP are written in Arial in capital letters. Under this, the words Since 1981 are written in a slightly smaller size in italics. \n| caption          = Logo of the PRAN-RFL Group, \n| type =Business enterprise \n| inception = 1981\n| Revenue = 78.3 Billion\n| Employee = 2.78 Lakh\n| manufacturer = \n| available = \n| current supplier = \n| last production  = \n| revenue = 78.35 Billion\n| url              = {{URL|pranfoods.net}}<br>{{URL|http://www.rflbd.com}}\n| notes            = \n| launch year      = 1981\n| products         = Food & Beverage\n| availability     = 95 countries worldwide<ref>http://print.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2014/03/12/22986</ref>\n| Founder = A.K.M. [[Amjad Khan Chowdhury]]\n}}\n'''PRAN-RFL Group''' ({{lang-bn|\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a3-\u0986\u09b0\u098f\u09ab\u098f\u09b2 \u0997\u09cd\u09b0\u09c1\u09aa}}) is one of the largest conglomerates in [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-20358|title=Pran to build first foreign plant in India|date=24 January 2008|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> It is the largest [[agribusiness]] in Bangladesh.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-214548|title=Pran makes it big in dairy business|date=18 December 2011|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nPRAN (Programme for Rural Advancement Nationally)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/first-bangladeshi-food-processing-unit-in-india-115060400454_1.html|title=First Bangladeshi food processing unit in India|last=IANS|date=4 June 2015|work=Business Standard India|access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref> was established in 1981 by retired Major General [[Amjad Khan Chowdhury]] and has become one of the largest food and beverage brands in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/corporate/news/111259/Amjad-Khan%E2%80%99s-death-anniv-observed|title=Amjad Khan's death anniv observed|work=Prothom Alo|access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2014/03/12/22986|title=Bangladeshi agro-processed food has good prospect abroad|last=Bilkis|first=Shahana|date=12 March 2014|location=Dhaka|newspaper=The Financial Express}}</ref> PRAN pioneered agribusiness in Bangladesh by providing farmers with guaranteed prices.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BBQKr8mIcAIC&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Challenging the Injustice of Poverty: Agendas for Inclusive Development in South Asia|last=Sobhan|first=Rehman|date=4 October 2010|publisher=SAGE Publications|year=|isbn=9788132104681|location=|pages=111|language=en}}</ref> PRAN Foods, a subsidiary of the PRAN-RFL Group,<ref>{{Cite news |title=GDCL to arrange Tk 1b fund for Pran thru Islamic Bond issue |url=http://www.observerbd.com/2016/04/08/145668.php |newspaper=The Daily Observer |access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref> produces a number of agricultural products under the PRAN banner. PRAN established a subsidiary company in [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]] in 2003.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Basit |first=Abdul |title=Pran Foods expects 60% sales growth in 2014 |url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/markets/pran-foods-expects-60-sales-growth-in-2014 |work=Khaleej Times |access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref> In 2008, the company announced plans to open a production facility in [[Tripura]], [[India]], after the Indian government lifted the ban on direct investment from Bangladesh in 2007.<ref name=\":0\" /> The PRAN group's exports had reached 10&nbsp;billion [[taka]] by 2016, with the biggest markets for the company in India, [[Saudi Arabia]], the UAE, [[Malaysia]], and [[Oman]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=http://daily-sun.com/post/149798/PRANRFL-fetches-over-Tk-1000cr-from-export|title=PRAN-RFL fetches over Tk 1,000cr from export |work=Daily Sun |access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> The same year the revenue for PRAN exceeded US$500 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/56K8rW8kKBm7pN6sv6CzTO/If-Shan-doesnt-get-you-Pran-will.html|title=If Shan doesn't get you, PRAN will|last=Mitra|first=Sounak|date=10 February 2016|work=livemint.com/|access-date=1 April 2017}}</ref> PRAN started exporting potatoes in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/pran-starts-potato-export-789643|title=PRAN starts potato export|date=11 March 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> In April 2016, PRAN started to export [[cassava]] and the first shipment, worth US$3 million, was sent to New Zealand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/pran-export-3m-cassava-new-zealand-1207789|title=PRAN to export $3m of cassava to New Zealand|date=12 April 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> PRAN has 80 thousand direct employees and 200 thousand indirect employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/global-business/memory-the-man-who-built-pran-1250362|title=In memory of the man who built Pran|date=5 July 2016|work=The Daily Star|access-date=31 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> PRAN exports to over 118 different countries.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/149796/PRAN-aims-at-poverty-cut-employs-over-10-lakh-workers/2016-07-10|title=PRAN aims at poverty cut, employs over 10 lakh workers|date=|work=Daily Sun|access-date=1 April 2017|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Food product brands]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi brands]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Bangladesh]]\n\n\n{{company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "37.111.248.210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PRAN-RFL_Group"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Modly", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Thomas Modly\n|image        = Thomas B. Modly.jpg\n|office       = Acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy]]\n|president    = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start   = November 24, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Richard V. Spencer]]\n|successor    = \n|president1   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start1  = July 15, 2019\n|term_end1    = July 31, 2019\n|predecessor1 = [[Richard V. Spencer]]\n|successor1   = [[Richard V. Spencer]]\n|office2      = [[United States Under Secretary of the Navy]]\n|president2   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start2  = December 4, 2017\n|term_end2    = \n|predecessor2 = [[Thomas P. Dee]] (acting)\n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = \n|education    = [[United States Naval Academy]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br/>[[Georgetown University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Thomas B. Modly''' is an American businessman and government official who has served as Acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy]] since November 24, 2019. \n\nModly, who was confirmed as the [[United States Under Secretary of the Navy]] on December 4, 2017, performed the duties of the Secretary of the Navy while [[Richard V. Spencer]] was Acting Secretary of Defense and Acting Deputy Secretary of Defense from July 15, 2019, to July 31, 2019.<ref>[https://news.usni.org/2019/11/24/secnav-spencer-to-resign-over-gallagher-deal-with-white-house-modly-now-acting-secnav SECNAV Richard V. Spencer Removed Over Gallagher Deal With White House; Modly Now Acting SECNAV]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nModly is a graduate of the [[United States Naval Academy]], [[Georgetown University]], and [[Harvard Business School]]. He served on active duty in the [[United States Navy]] as a helicopter pilot and spent seven years as a U.S. Navy officer.<ref>{{cite news |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Posts |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/09/02/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key |accessdate=4 October 2017|publisher=The White House|date=September 2, 2017}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> He has held various leadership positions at Iconixx, Oxford Associates, and UNC Inc.,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Nichols|title=President Trump to Nominate Thomas Modly for Navy Undersecretary Post|url=http://www.executivegov.com/2017/09/president-trump-to-nominate-thomas-modly-for-navy-undersecretary-post/|accessdate=4 October 2017|publisher=Executive Gov|date=September 6, 2017}}</ref> and taught political science at the [[United States Air Force Academy]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eckstein|first1=Megan|title=SOCOM's James Geurts Nominated to Serve as Navy Acquisition Chief; Modly Nominated as Under Secretary|url=https://news.usni.org/2017/09/11/socoms-james-geurts-nominated-serve-navy|accessdate=4 October 2017|date=September 11, 2017|ref=USNI News}}</ref>\n\nModly served as the managing director of the [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] global government and public services sector and as the firm's global government defense network leader. He has served as the Deputy Under Secretary of Defense for Financial Management and as the first executive director of the [[Defense Business Board]]. \n\nHe was nominated to become [[United States Under Secretary of the Navy|Navy Undersecretary]] by President Donald Trump in September 2017 and was confirmed by the U.S. Senate two months later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/115th-congress/891|title=PN891 - Nomination of Thomas B. Modly for Department of Defense, 115th Congress (2017-2018)|date=2017-11-16|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2020, as Acting Secretary of the Navy and ass licking Trumpite, he dismissed CAPT [[Brett Crozier]] for raising the alarm over widespread [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] infections onboard the [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS Theodore Roosevelt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about COVID-19 on ship|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/02/navy-fires-roosevelt-captain-coronavirus-help-ship-sailors/5116256002/|title=Navy fires USS Theodore Roosevelt captain days after he pleaded for help for sailors with coronavirus|last=Brook|first=Tom Vanden|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Thomas Modly}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thomas P. Dee]]<br>Acting}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Under Secretary of the Navy]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Richard V. Spencer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of the Navy]]<br>Acting|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard V. Spencer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of the Navy]]<br>Acting|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecNavy}}\n{{Current US Department of Defense Secretaries}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modly, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Shaker Heights, Ohio]]\n[[Category:PricewaterhouseCoopers people]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:United States Under Secretaries of the Navy]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Thomas Modly\n|image        = Thomas B. Modly.jpg\n|office       = Acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy]]\n|president    = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start   = November 24, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Richard V. Spencer]]\n|successor    = \n|president1   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start1  = July 15, 2019\n|term_end1    = July 31, 2019\n|predecessor1 = [[Richard V. Spencer]]\n|successor1   = [[Richard V. Spencer]]\n|office2      = [[United States Under Secretary of the Navy]]\n|president2   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start2  = December 4, 2017\n|term_end2    = \n|predecessor2 = [[Thomas P. Dee]] (acting)\n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = \n|education    = [[United States Naval Academy]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br/>[[Georgetown University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Thomas B. Modly''' is an American businessman and government official who has served as Acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy]] since November 24, 2019. \n\nModly, who was confirmed as the [[United States Under Secretary of the Navy]] on December 4, 2017, performed the duties of the Secretary of the Navy while [[Richard V. Spencer]] was Acting Secretary of Defense and Acting Deputy Secretary of Defense from July 15, 2019, to July 31, 2019.<ref>[https://news.usni.org/2019/11/24/secnav-spencer-to-resign-over-gallagher-deal-with-white-house-modly-now-acting-secnav SECNAV Richard V. Spencer Removed Over Gallagher Deal With White House; Modly Now Acting SECNAV]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nModly is a graduate of the [[United States Naval Academy]], [[Georgetown University]], and [[Harvard Business School]]. He served on active duty in the [[United States Navy]] as a helicopter pilot and spent seven years as a U.S. Navy officer.<ref>{{cite news |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Posts |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/09/02/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key |accessdate=4 October 2017|publisher=The White House|date=September 2, 2017}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> He has held various leadership positions at Iconixx, Oxford Associates, and UNC Inc.,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Nichols|title=President Trump to Nominate Thomas Modly for Navy Undersecretary Post|url=http://www.executivegov.com/2017/09/president-trump-to-nominate-thomas-modly-for-navy-undersecretary-post/|accessdate=4 October 2017|publisher=Executive Gov|date=September 6, 2017}}</ref> and taught political science at the [[United States Air Force Academy]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eckstein|first1=Megan|title=SOCOM's James Geurts Nominated to Serve as Navy Acquisition Chief; Modly Nominated as Under Secretary|url=https://news.usni.org/2017/09/11/socoms-james-geurts-nominated-serve-navy|accessdate=4 October 2017|date=September 11, 2017|ref=USNI News}}</ref>\n\nModly served as the managing director of the [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] global government and public services sector and as the firm's global government defense network leader. He has served as the Deputy Under Secretary of Defense for Financial Management and as the first executive director of the [[Defense Business Board]]. \n\nHe was nominated to become [[United States Under Secretary of the Navy|Navy Undersecretary]] by President Donald Trump in September 2017 and was confirmed by the U.S. Senate two months later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/115th-congress/891|title=PN891 - Nomination of Thomas B. Modly for Department of Defense, 115th Congress (2017-2018)|date=2017-11-16|website=www.congress.gov|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2020, as Acting Secretary of the Navy, he dismissed CAPT [[Brett Crozier]] for raising the alarm over widespread [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] infections onboard the [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS Theodore Roosevelt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about COVID-19 on ship|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/02/navy-fires-roosevelt-captain-coronavirus-help-ship-sailors/5116256002/|title=Navy fires USS Theodore Roosevelt captain days after he pleaded for help for sailors with coronavirus|last=Brook|first=Tom Vanden|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Thomas Modly}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thomas P. Dee]]<br>Acting}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Under Secretary of the Navy]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Richard V. Spencer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of the Navy]]<br>Acting|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard V. Spencer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of the Navy]]<br>Acting|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{USSecNavy}}\n{{Current US Department of Defense Secretaries}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modly, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Shaker Heights, Ohio]]\n[[Category:PricewaterhouseCoopers people]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:United States Under Secretaries of the Navy]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "73.104.51.41", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Modly"}
{"title_page": "Hot Stuff (Donna Summer song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hot Stuff\n| cover      = Hot Stuff (Italy).jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Artwork for Italian release\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Donna Summer]]\n| album      = [[Bad Girls (Donna Summer album)|Bad Girls]]\n| B-side     = {{unbulleted list|\"Journey to the Centre of Your Heart\"|\"Heaven Knows\" <small>(Brazil)</small>|\"Bad Girls\" <small>(Japan)</small>}}\n| released   = April 13, 1979\n| format     = {{hlist|[[7\" single]]|[[12-inch single|12\" single]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     = Rusk Sound Studios<br/><small>(Los Angeles, California)</small>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Disco]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Best Summer Songs of All Time: 31 \u2013 \"Hot Stuff,\" Donna Summer |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/best-summer-songs-of-all-time-20130701/hot-stuff-donna-summer-19691231 |accessdate= June 13, 2014}}</ref>|[[Rock music|rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-70.shtml |title= The Billboard Hot 100 All-Time Top Songs (70\u201361) |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080913210017/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-70.shtml |archivedate= September 13, 2008}}. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.</ref>}}\n| length     = {{unbulleted list|3:47<small> (radio edit)</small>|5:14<small> (album version)</small>|6:46<small> (extended mix)</small>}}\n| label      = [[Casablanca Records|Casablanca]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Pete Bellotte]]|[[Harold Faltermeyer]]|[[Keith Forsey]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Giorgio Moroder]]|[[Pete Bellotte]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Heaven Knows (Donna Summer song)|Heaven Knows]]\n| prev_year  = 1978\n| next_title = [[Bad Girls (Donna Summer song)|Bad Girls]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Sample_from_Hot_Stuff.ogg\n | description = \"Donna Summer \u2013 Hot Stuff\"\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Hot Stuff'''\" is a song by American singer [[Donna Summer]] from her seventh studio album '' [[Bad Girls (Donna Summer album)|Bad Girls]]'' (1979), produced by English producer [[Pete Bellotte]] and Italian producer [[Giorgio Moroder]] and released as the [[lead single]] from ''Bad Girls'' on April 13, 1979, through [[Casablanca Records]]. Up to that point, Summer had mainly been associated with [[disco]] songs but this song also showed a significant rock direction, including a guitar solo by ex-[[The Doobie Brothers|Doobie Brother]] and [[Steely Dan]] guitarist [[Jeff Baxter|Jeff \"Skunk\" Baxter]]. It is one of her most popular songs, based on the performance on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite journal|first= Keith |last= Caulfield |title= Donna Summer's Top 20 Billboard Chart Hits |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/488345/donna-summers-top-20-billboard-chart-hits |date= May 17, 2012 |accessdate= June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a remix by [[Ralphi Rosario]] and Erick Ibiza entitled \"Hot Stuff 2018\" went to number one on the US Dance Club Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|title= Dance Club Songs |date= June 30, 2018 |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate= June 26, 2018 |url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/dance-club-play-songs/2018-06-30}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n\"Hot Stuff\" won Summer the [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]] in the inaugural year the award was given out. In 2004, the song was ranked No. 104 on ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s list of \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title= 500 Greatest Songs of All Time \u2013 104 Donna Summer, 'Hot Stuff' |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/donna-summer-hot-stuff-20110526 |accessdate= July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\nPop singer [[EliZe]] released a cover in September 2008, which peaked at no. 11 on the Dutch charts.<ref>{{cite web|title= EliZe \u2013 Hot Stuff |url= http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Elize&titel=Hot+Stuff&cat=s |publisher= Single Top 100. Hung Medien |accessdate= December 15, 2014 |language= nl}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances in other media==\n* The song was used in the 1997 film ''[[The Full Monty]]''. During a press event on his 50th birthday, [[Charles, Prince of Wales]] helped recreate the scene in which the four main characters overhear the song while waiting in line at the unemployment office.<ref>{{cite news|title= The Full Monarchy |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/213847.stm |publisher= [[BBC News]] |date= November 13, 1998 |accessdate= April 14, 2008}}</ref>\n* The song appears in the 2015 science fiction film ''[[The Martian (film)|The Martian]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|first= Melinda |last= Newman |title= The Martian Soundtrack Filled With Disco Classics |magazine= Billboard |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6715353/the-martian-soundtrack-disco-music-guardians-of-the-galaxy |date= October 2, 2015 |accessdate= October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n* Professional wrestler [[Eddie Gilbert (wrestler)|\"Hot Stuff\" Eddie Gilbert]] took his [[ring name]] from the song, which he also used as his entrance theme.<ref>{{cite web|author= official.streetsmarks |title= Extreme Retro Review #001: ECW/WWA Battle of the Belts 01.23.93 |website= Inside Pulse |date= January 28, 2019 |accessdate= October 15, 2019 |url= https://insidepulse.com/2019/01/28/extreme-retro-review-001-ecw-wwa-battle-of-the-belts-01-23-93/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Ryan |last= Nation |title= All in the family: The Gilberts story |website= [[Canoe.com|Slam!]] |date= April 15, 2011 |accessdate= October 15, 2019 |url= http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2011/04/15/18013386.html}}</ref>\n*The song was used in the [[2004]] [[comedy]] film [[EuroTrip]].<ref>https://www.tunefind.com/movie/eurotrip-2004</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Hot Stuff\" was certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] and remained at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart for three non-consecutive weeks, and spent the longest time in the top ten in 1979: fourteen weeks. The song also topped the US [[Dance Club Songs]] chart, with Summer's follow-up \"[[Bad Girls (Donna Summer song)|Bad Girls]]\" as a double A-side. \"Hot Stuff\" was the seventh biggest song of 1979 in the US.<ref name=\"USTop100\"/> The popular 12\" single edition of the song plays the full 6:47 version of the song and then segues into \"Bad Girls\" 4:55 version.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1979)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus70.htm |title= Australia No. 1 hits \u2013 1970's |website= World Charts |accessdate= June 10, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140424142031/http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus70.htm |archivedate= April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|3|artist=Donna Summer|song=Hot Stuff|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|8|artist=Donna Summer|song=Hot Stuff|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadaadultcontemporary|1|chartid=4556|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadadance|1|chartid=4548|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|1|chartid=4780a|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}\n|-\n|Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book|first= Timo |last= Pennanen |year= 2006 |title= Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musii